 - State recognition of marriage is not a religious matter.  Justices of the peace regularly perform non-religious civil marriages.<br>
<br>
2) Some religions perform same-sex unions and marriages.<br>
 - Not every Christian denomination has as narrow-minded a view as you do, Ziderax.  I am an Unitarian-Universalist, and our church has long performed same-sex unions (for more than 20 years).  So do some Methodist denominations, as well as some Episcopalian and Lutheran denominations.  The Metropolitan Community Church, an evangelical Chrisian denomination, was founded by a gay man for gay men and lesbians and performs same-sex unions.  Furthermore, many Reformed Jewish synagogues also perform same-sex unions.<br>
<br>
You claim that the state recognition of same-sex marriage would &quot;force&quot; someone else's religious views upon you, but you wish to force your religious views upon those of us who do not share them with you.  Entire Christian denominations disagree with you.<br>
<br>
If you don't like same-sex marriage, don't marry another man.  It's that easy.  No one's going to force you to.<br>
<br>
Allowing same-sex marriage will not force any denomination to perform same-sex unions that does not want to perform them.  They are free to perform, or not perform, any marriage ceremony they so choose.<br>
<br>
In fact, Ziderax, you're the one violating my right to freedom of religion.  In my denomination, same-sex marriage is allowed.  However, people like you don't like the fact that not everyone believes as you do, and fight to restrict others' freedoms.<br>
<br>
The perversity of your argument is that you argue for restricting someone else's freedom of religion in the name of your own.<br>
<br>
